    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-01T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-01T06:00:00-05:00" n="500"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d500">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/708: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-01T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 1, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received August 1—7:08
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>258. Private negotiations are in progress between the British, French and
                    Italians with conversations with the Abyssinians. The current <pb facs="0724"
                        n="622" xml:id="pg_622"/> aspect of these negotiations is that the French
                    have gained the middle position between Great Britain and Italy, negotiating
                    with the British from the vantage point of prior understandings with the
                    Italians while the British are thus far unsuccessfully striving to arrange with
                    the French a common front to present to the Italians. The relationship between
                    Abyssinia and France and between Abyssinia and Great Britain remains here
                    exceedingly obscure as well as the entire matter of Abyssinian policy or tactics
                    vis-à-vis the League, the general impression being, however, that their
                    diplomacy is not in good hands.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
